# 6. Working summary

```{r working-summary, results='asis'}
cat(
  '<div class="callout"><h4>Working summary</h4>',
  '<p>This analysis is meant to connect the outcome families rather than test the intervention directly. ',
  'The clearest pattern is that some outcomes move together, but the full set of outcomes does not behave like one single assessment scale.</p>',
  '<ul>',
  '<li><strong>Prior knowledge is strongly related to open-response conceptual performance</strong> and also relates to value-estimation performance. This supports using prior knowledge as a covariate when interpreting conceptual outcomes.</li>',
  '<li><strong>Open-response conceptual score is moderately related to value-estimation performance</strong>, suggesting that verbal conceptual explanation and numeric estimation share some common understanding.</li>',
  '<li><strong>Add-points correct direction is only weakly related to open response and modestly related to value estimation.</strong> This suggests that the add-points task may involve additional interaction/planning demands beyond conceptual knowledge alone.</li>',
  '<li><strong>Add-points slope preservation is largely uncorrelated with the other outcomes.</strong> This may mean that preserving slope while changing correlation is a distinct and difficult skill, or that the slope-preservation metric is noisy.</li>',
  '<li><strong>Interest subscales are strongly related to each other</strong> and show modest positive relationships with some conceptual outcomes, especially open-response score and choose-r accuracy.</li>',
  '</ul>',
  '<p>For reporting, I would use this as a synthesis/sanity check. ',
  'The condition-level models remain the main evidence for intervention effects, while this report helps explain why different outcome families may show different patterns.</p>',
  '</div>'
)
